  "prompt": "How? Ant walks from corner A (bottom left) of front wall to the other corner C (bottom right) of rear wall of a 3 meter cubical room. Shortest route?",
  "response": "To find the shortest route for the ant from corner A (bottom left of the front wall) to corner C (bottom right of the rear wall) in a 3-meter cubical room, we need to think about the geometry of the cube and the possible paths.\n\nImagine unfolding the cube into a 2-dimensional plane. When you do this, the ant's shortest path can be visualized on this plane. Here's one way to think about it:\n\n1. **Unfolding the cube:** Flatten the cube such that the paths to the opposite corners are visible.\n   \n2. **Path visualization:** The corners A and C can be connected in the unfolded plane, taking the shortest possible straight line.\n\nGiven that the room is 3 meters in all dimensions:\n- Corner A is at coordinate (0, 0, 0).\n- Corner C is at (3, 3, 3).\n\nNow consider the route in 2D after unfolding:\n\n```\nConsider the cube faces (\\ means 'continue on another face):\n\nA---D\n|   |  \n|   | \nB   E\n|   |\n|   |\nF---C\n```\n\nOne unfolded plan:\nA is at vertex (0, 0)\nC at vertex (6, 3)\n\nTo get the shortest distance, calculate the Euclidean distance between these two points:\nLet's consider any unfolded version but commonly it is:\nShortest distance travel directly from unfolded corner:\n\nUsing the distance formula `d = \u221a((x2 - x1)\u00b2 + (y2 - y1)\u00b2)`:\nd = \u221a((6-0)\u00b2 + (3-0)\u00b2)\nd = \u221a(36 + 9)\nd = \u221a45\nd = 3\u221a5 \u2248 6.708 meters\n\nUltimately, the ant would travel diagonally across the faces of the cube, which unfolds into a straight line distance:\nThe shortest route the ant can take is approximately 6.708 meters.",
